// =====================================================================
// REJECTED — Rule 4A: Tool Shadowing recipient/body entity mismatch
// =====================================================================
//
// STATUS: This rule was designed and then REJECTED during verification
// against lab data on 2026-05-22. It is preserved here as an artifact
// of the design exploration. It is NOT deployed and should NOT be
// committed to /rules/. The reasons for rejection are documented below.
//
// Design intent: Detect send_email tool calls where the recipient
// address does not appear as an email entity anywhere in the body.
// Premise: in legitimate emails, the recipient is typically referenced
// in the body (by email address, in greetings, in signatures, or in
// forwarded content). When the LLM constructs a tool call whose
// recipient is decoupled from any body entity, the recipient was
// likely set by something other than the user's intent.
//
// Why it was rejected: verification against the lab baseline dataset
// revealed that legitimate short emails do not reference the recipient
// in the body at all. The actual data showed:
//
//   - ClaudeDesktop legitimate rows: body = "Hi Alice. How are you?"
//     or "Hi Alice" — addresses the recipient by NAME, not by email
//     address. The extract_all() regex returns an empty email set
//     from the body, and the recipient (alice@mail.com) is not in
//     that empty set, so the rule fires — a false positive on
//     legitimate traffic.
//
//   - ollmcp rows: body = "Hi, just checking in" — does not
//     reference the recipient at all (no name, no email). This
//     phrasing is recipient-agnostic. The same body appears with
//     both the legitimate recipient (alice@mail.com) AND the
//     hijacked recipient (attacker@pwnd.com). The rule's logic
//     cannot distinguish legitimate from hijacked when the body
//     contains no recipient identifier of any kind.
//
// Two follow-up design variants were considered and also rejected:
//
//   Variant A — local-part name matching: extract 'alice' from
//   'alice@mail.com' and check whether the body contains 'alice'
//   (case-insensitive). Rejected because short legitimate bodies
//   like "Hi, just checking in" do not contain the local-part
//   either — same false-positive failure mode.
//
//   Variant B — combined email-or-name matching: check for either
//   the email address OR the local-part name in the body. Rejected
//   for the same fundamental reason: bodies that don't reference
//   the recipient at all are LEGITIMATE in short casual emails,
//   not anomalous.
//
// Root cause of the rejection: Rule 4A's underlying premise — that
// the recipient should be referenced in the body — is empirically
// false for short casual emails. The detection signature is built
// on the absence of a marker that legitimate emails routinely also
// lack. The rule cannot distinguish "legitimate short email" from
// "hijacked short email" based on body content alone.
//
// Why this matters for the project narrative: the rejection was not
// a design flaw caught early — it was caught by VERIFICATION AGAINST
// REAL LAB DATA, which is the discipline that this project has held
// throughout. The same verify-before-design discipline that caught
// the TimeGenerated table-layer binding bug and the user-prompt
// data absence also caught this. Recording the rejected design
// preserves the integrity of the iterative reasoning.
//
// Replacement: Rule 4 was narrowed to the 'Original recipient:'
// structural tell detection only — a detection grounded in an
// artifact the attack itself produces, rather than the absence of
// a marker in legitimate emails. See:
//   rules/rule_04_original_recipient_tell.kql
//
// Authored: 2026-05-22 (Day 3 design exploration)
// Status set to REJECTED: 2026-05-22 (Sub-task 3 baseline verification)
// =====================================================================

// THE KQL BELOW IS PRESERVED AS THE REJECTED DESIGN. DO NOT DEPLOY.

MCPProtocolLogs_CL
| where EventType == "ToolCallInvoked"
| where HostApp == "ClaudeDesktop"
| where ToolName == "send_email"
| where isnotnull(EventTime)
| where EventTime > ago(7d)
| extend Recipient = tostring(CallParameters.recipient)
| extend Body = tostring(CallParameters.body)
| where isnotempty(Body)
| extend BodyEmails = extract_all(@"[\w\.-]+@[\w\.-]+\.\w+", Body)
| where Recipient !in (BodyEmails)
| project
    EventTime,
    SessionId,
    HostApp,
    ModelName,
    ToolName,
    Recipient,
    Body,
    BodyEmails,
    UserPromptHash,
    CallId
